Plaid
Plaid has become the connective tissue of the modern financial ecosystem. By enabling applications to securely connect with users' bank accounts, Plaid powers a staggering range of financial products across lending, payments, wealth management, and personal finance.

In 2026, Plaid's B2B value proposition has deepened considerably. Its identity verification, income verification, and transaction data products are now foundational to how lenders, insurers, and FinTech companies underwrite risk and verify financial information. Plaid's network spans thousands of financial institutions and millions of end users, making it an infrastructure layer that is increasingly difficult to route around.

For B2B companies in the lending, HR tech, or financial services space, integrating Plaid is no longer a differentiator. It is effectively a baseline requirement. What makes Plaid notable in 2026 is its continued expansion into more sophisticated data products and its investment in open banking infrastructure as regulatory frameworks evolve.

What is open banking and why does it matter for your business in 2026? Open banking refers to the practice of financial institutions sharing data with third-party providers through secure APIs. Plaid is one of the primary enablers of this ecosystem in the United States, and its continued growth reflects how central data connectivity has become to modern financial operations.

Robinhood
Robinhood's transformation into a serious B2B and institutional FinTech player is one of the defining stories of 2026. Originally a consumer-facing brokerage known for commission-free trading, Robinhood has expanded its product suite to include retirement accounts, credit cards, banking services, and increasingly, tools that serve professional and business users.

Robinhood's 2026 strategy reflects a broader ambition to become a comprehensive financial platform. Its B2B relevance lies in its infrastructure plays, its approach to democratizing access to financial markets for a broader range of businesses and investors, and its growing role as a platform for new financial product distribution.

For FinTech marketers, Robinhood represents both a distribution channel and a competitor to watch. Its large, highly engaged user base and its willingness to move fast and challenge incumbents make it a company that shapes market expectations even beyond the segments it directly serves.

Coinbase
Coinbase has cemented its position as the most prominent regulated cryptocurrency exchange and blockchain infrastructure provider in the United States. In 2026, its B2B significance has expanded dramatically as institutional adoption of digital assets continues to accelerate and regulatory clarity improves.

Coinbase Prime, the company's institutional product, serves hedge funds, asset managers, banks, and corporations that need secure custody, trading, and reporting capabilities for digital assets. Coinbase's Base network, an Ethereum Layer 2 blockchain, has become a significant platform for developers building decentralized financial applications.

For B2B companies in financial services, the relevant question in 2026 is no longer whether to engage with digital assets, but how. Coinbase provides the regulatory compliance, security infrastructure, and product depth that enterprise clients require to do so responsibly. Its compliance-first approach and its relationships with US regulators make it the default choice for institutions entering the digital asset space.

Affirm
Affirm has redefined buy now, pay later in the B2B context, moving beyond its consumer origins to build a powerful set of solutions for enterprise merchants and financial partners. In 2026, Affirm's platform enables businesses to offer flexible payment terms to their customers while managing risk through Affirm's underwriting infrastructure.

What distinguishes Affirm from competitors is its data-driven approach to credit decisioning. Unlike traditional credit card companies, Affirm uses thousands of data points to make real-time underwriting decisions, enabling it to serve customers who may not have access to traditional credit while managing default risk effectively.

For B2B buyers in retail, healthcare, travel, and services, Affirm's merchant platform offers a proven mechanism to increase average order values, improve conversion rates, and expand the addressable customer base. Affirm's 2026 product expansion includes deeper integration with enterprise ERP and commerce platforms, making it easier to embed into existing business workflows.

Brex
Brex has established itself as the financial operating system for modern businesses, particularly high-growth startups and venture-backed companies. Its corporate card, expense management, business banking, and bill pay products are built natively for the speed and complexity of fast-scaling organizations.

In 2026, Brex has expanded its focus to serve mid-market and enterprise clients, broadening its addressable market significantly. Its AI-powered expense management platform, which automates categorization, policy enforcement, and financial reporting, has become a genuine differentiator in a crowded space.

For B2B finance and operations leaders, Brex's integrated approach eliminates the patchwork of tools that most companies rely on for expense management, corporate cards, and reimbursements. Its 2026 product roadmap emphasizes deeper ERP integrations and advanced analytics, positioning it as a strategic financial partner rather than a tactical tool.

A common question from finance teams: Can a single platform really replace our existing expense management, corporate card, and banking stack? For many organizations evaluating Brex in 2026, the answer is increasingly yes.

SoFi
SoFi has completed one of the more impressive transformations in FinTech, evolving from a student loan refinancing company into a fully chartered bank with a diverse suite of financial products for both consumers and businesses. In 2026, SoFi's B2B relevance is most pronounced through its Galileo and Technisys divisions, which provide the infrastructure that powers hundreds of FinTech applications and financial products worldwide.

Galileo, acquired by SoFi in 2020, processes billions of transactions annually and provides the account and payment processing infrastructure for some of the best-known names in FinTech. Technisys brings core banking technology that enables financial institutions to modernize their operations without full system replacements.

For B2B technology buyers in financial services, SoFi's infrastructure stack represents a compelling alternative to legacy core banking providers. Its cloud-native architecture, modern API design, and track record with innovative FinTech clients give it significant credibility in enterprise conversations.

